WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.120
Welcome, everyone, to the Data Science Hangout. And welcome back to many of you have joined

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:15.280
us here in the following past few weeks. But just for anyone who's new to this, and to

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:20.400
Joel, thank you so much for joining us. This is an open space for current and aspiring

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:26.400
data science leaders to just be able to connect and ask each other questions. And really,

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:33.520
today, Joel, we're excited to be able to pick your brain a little bit. And so for the sessions,

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:39.040
we really want to focus on any questions that are most important to you all here. So you can

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:46.639
jump in live or put questions in the chat. And we also have a Slido link, which Rob will put in the

00:00:46.639 --> 00:00:52.560
chat window right now. So you can ask anonymous questions there too. But just a little heads up

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:57.840
that it will be recorded for people that missed it. So it'll be shared up to YouTube. But you

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:04.000
always have that option of anonymous questions as well. But I'm so grateful to be joined by my

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.959
co host for today, Joel Pepera, the Director of Data Science at GEICO. And Joel, I'd love to have

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:15.599
you introduce yourself and maybe share a bit about your team and the work that you do.

00:01:16.639 --> 00:01:20.879
Sure, absolutely. And thank you for having me. I'm excited to talk to everyone today.

00:01:21.599 --> 00:01:27.120
As Rachel mentioned, I am the Director of Data Science at GEICO. Pretty much all of the data

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:32.720
science activities roll up through me. We do have other analytics teams and professionals

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:36.959
scattered throughout other parts of the organization. But all the core data science

00:01:36.959 --> 00:01:42.320
work that we do falls under my purview. I've been at GEICO for quite a long time,

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:49.599
coming up on 14 years. My professional background is primarily in the actuarial space. So I'm a

00:01:49.599 --> 00:01:55.279
credentialed actuary, which is an insurance specific profession. It deals with a lot of

00:01:55.279 --> 00:02:01.120
things that are, let's say, similar to data science. So using data and predictive analytics

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:08.880
and statistics to estimate things, predict values of interest. And in insurance, it's primarily

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:16.479
assessing customer risk so that we can understand that from a pricing and financial planning

00:02:16.479 --> 00:02:23.279
perspective. So that's what I did for most of my early career. And then about three or four years

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:30.880
ago, pivoted into a broader data science role. And we've been building up our team and our

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:39.520
capabilities within GEICO pretty aggressively. At GEICO, we focus on three main areas of impact for

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:45.679
data science. One is in our product development area. The second is in our customer experience,

00:02:45.679 --> 00:02:50.800
dealing with how we interact with customers in marketing channels, customer service channels,

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:57.360
et cetera. And then the third major area is our claims division, which deals with how we assess

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:03.440
damages and injuries when people are involved in auto accidents. There's a lot of interesting

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:10.240
use cases there around fraud detection or triaging, estimating payment amounts and things like that.

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:17.679
Some use cases, I think dealing with data and statistics is not new, but certainly a lot

00:03:17.679 --> 00:03:23.679
of the technological evolution going on, not just in insurance, but more broadly is

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:29.919
causing us to think a little bit differently about things than we have in the past. And it opens up

00:03:29.919 --> 00:03:36.479
a lot of really exciting opportunities for us to mature and move forward as a company.

00:03:37.039 --> 00:03:44.080
One of the primary areas that I'm most excited about right now is telematics, which for those

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:49.839
who aren't familiar is an initiative within insurance and other industries as well, where

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:56.639
due to the technology on modern smartphones or increasingly technology embedded in vehicles

00:03:56.639 --> 00:04:05.119
directly, we can, with the customer's consent, of course, understand in a very detailed granular way

00:04:05.119 --> 00:04:11.839
how our customers or potential customers are operating their vehicle and get a much

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:18.720
more granular assessment of the risk profile. So that's something that I think in general is

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:23.119
a big focus for companies in auto insurance and certainly Geico is among them. So

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:29.519
there's a lot of really exciting potential for data science in that domain in particular.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:34.720
That's awesome. And so the team's just starting now to use telematics or how are you starting to

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:41.040
do this today? Yeah, well, I wouldn't say we're starting. We've been working with this for a

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:48.559
little bit now. It's not, I think, a new phenomenon in insurance. Some companies have been, at least

00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:56.079
in an R&D capacity, been working on this for several years. But I think several market factors

00:04:56.799 --> 00:05:02.399
are increasing the focus. One is just the technology is changing. Smartphones are obviously

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:08.559
ubiquitous now, and that provides a cost-effective way of collecting data. I also think that

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:13.760
consumer attitudes around privacy and sharing data are evolving. Of course, there are still

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:19.279
concerns, and that will continue to be a factor. But I really think the pandemic has impacted that

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:26.640
in some meaningful ways. Obviously, when lockdown started occurring, people's driving behavior

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:31.760
changed, and therefore, their risk exposure changed. And one of the things we saw was people

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:36.239
were realizing, my insurance rates aren't as responsive as maybe they ought to be to how

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:44.320
my use of my vehicle is changing. And you saw a lot of companies do some large-scale measures

00:05:45.119 --> 00:05:51.839
to provide people discounts or refund premiums and things like that. But I think it's also

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:59.279
pointing to an opportunity to just have a pricing model that is, in general, more responsive

00:05:59.279 --> 00:06:05.519
to how people are operating their vehicle. And that creates a value proposition that I think

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:12.079
more people are comfortable with in terms of exchanging some of their data, some of their

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:21.040
data for that value. And how does the team, or I'm just curious myself, how does the team

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:25.519
get all of that data? It seems like there's so many different streams of data that would be

00:06:25.519 --> 00:06:32.079
coming in. Yeah, it's a good question. So you pretty much have to have a cloud-based approach

00:06:32.079 --> 00:06:38.320
here. We're talking about sensor-level data. It's very large volumes, and we're talking petabyte

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:43.920
scale. It really kind of depends on how many customers and what your enrollment rates look

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:52.480
like. But for us, it's very large. So it's a significant data engineering effort to collect

00:06:52.480 --> 00:07:01.760
that data, curate it, make it ready for applying models, training, and inferencing on those data

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:08.720
feeds. So it's a big effort. I would say it's at least as big on the data engineering side as it

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:15.519
is on the data science and machine learning side. So those two things go hand in hand. I mean,

00:07:15.519 --> 00:07:21.600
I think that's true in general with data science, but in particular, at the scale we're talking,

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:27.279
that's a critical consideration. Definitely. I'm starting to see a few questions coming in from

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:32.640
the audience. And Chris, I see you just asked one in the chat. Do you want to

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:34.239
ask that live and introduce yourself?

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:44.160
Sure, absolutely. Hello, everyone. I'm Chris Scheibel. I have been doing data analytics

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:52.000
for the past 24 years, active duty military, retired, and now got myself slid into a data

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:58.799
science role. So some of the things that I'm trying to get more collective on besides

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:06.079
all the statistical stuff in that is understanding more of the tools that my fellow data scientists

00:08:06.079 --> 00:08:10.880
out there that are using, besides the fact of, you know, things like Python, Pandas.

00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:19.440
I know RStudio is a big thing. I'm currently working on Shiny applications where I'm at as

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:23.920
well. But I was just kind of curious as far as maybe some of the other tools out there that

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:27.279
folks are using that I might be able to dive into and utilize.

00:08:29.119 --> 00:08:34.640
Yeah, good question. I think you listed off a lot of the key ones, you know, from a,

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:40.960
certainly from a machine learning model training perspective, R and Python are kind of the core

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:49.359
languages. Our team, I would say, mostly develops in Python, but there are some users in Geico

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:55.440
that are heavy R users as well. So both of those, I think, are great languages to learn.

00:08:57.599 --> 00:09:01.200
You know, sort of the dirty secret, although I don't think it's a secret anymore about data

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:08.239
sciences, you spend a lot of your time in data preparation. So I think the more adept you are

00:09:08.239 --> 00:09:14.559
with languages like SQL or Spark is a big one that we use a lot just based on the scale of our data.

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:26.239
So learning languages, like Scala, or, you know, the SQL interface into Spark, we often use

00:09:26.799 --> 00:09:32.880
PySpark pretty heavily. So you know, there are different interfaces into Spark, but just being

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:38.960
comfortable with optimizing data processing jobs in a distributed setting, I think is a good

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:48.479
investment of time. For us, it's mainly a combination of Spark and Python with a good

00:09:48.479 --> 00:09:54.960
amount of SQL as well. And then I think a lot of it sort of depends on, you know, beyond that,

00:09:54.960 --> 00:10:00.880
which I think is the core, a lot of it depends on what the role of a data scientist is in a

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:07.200
particular company. And that can vary quite a bit. Some of them find themselves more

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:13.119
involved in some of the low-level data engineering, where you might want to

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:18.000
familiarize yourself with data ingestion technologies, you know, Kafka or,

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:23.919
you know, some of the streaming technologies. Some data scientists tend to find themselves

00:10:23.919 --> 00:10:28.320
getting more involved in the front-end development, you know, where they might

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:34.719
need to use, you know, web development technologies, JavaScript, those sorts of things. So

00:10:34.719 --> 00:10:40.960
some of that will depend on just where you're situated in the overall kind of development stack.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:48.799
But I would say Spark, SQL, and Python are kind of the core technologies that I would focus on.

00:10:50.960 --> 00:10:54.479
Thank you for that insight, Joel. I greatly appreciate that. And now that means I can

00:10:54.479 --> 00:10:57.919
go ahead and add to my list of things I need to start learning.

00:10:57.919 --> 00:11:07.840
Sounds good. As a, I guess, kind of a follow-up question to that, Trevor, I see you're asking

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:14.000
around how much time does the team spend doing data analytics versus data science?

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.799
Trevor, did you want to jump in and add any context there?

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:24.640
Good morning. Good morning again, or good afternoon, depending on where you are.

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:30.479
I'm just very curious, you know, the field of data science continues to evolve.

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:37.440
I've seen so many definitions of data science, so many definitions of data analytics.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:46.640
I think the conclusion I'm working with in terms of defining data science is more around

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:53.520
building predictive models. I mean, that's where I see the literature going towards. So I know

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:59.679
that not all the problems that we try to solve in a company can be solved by data science.

00:12:00.479 --> 00:12:06.479
Some of it is actually analyzing basic data, basic descriptions. So I really wanted to find out,

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:11.520
most times when I talk to people on data science teams, I really want to find out

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:16.400
how much of their time is really spent building, fine-tuning, maintaining models

00:12:17.039 --> 00:12:22.479
as in data science versus trying to answer everyday basic questions.

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:31.280
Yeah, I think a good question. As you mentioned, this can vary quite a bit across different

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:35.280
industries or different companies within the industry. And I think a lot of it depends on

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:40.719
the overall maturity of their organization from a sort of data and analytics perspective.

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:49.760
At GEICO, we have a lot of traditional analytics teams that will apply statistical methods or

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:54.719
various analytical techniques to derive insights, make recommendations to

00:12:55.280 --> 00:13:01.359
some business consumers, build reports and those sorts of things. So at GEICO, our data science

00:13:01.359 --> 00:13:07.119
team tries to focus more on core data science work, which I would consider to be, like you

00:13:07.119 --> 00:13:11.919
mentioned, training predictive models, building machine learning systems, and most

00:13:12.239 --> 00:13:18.799
of what we do is large-scale systems that can directly impact business processes through some

00:13:18.799 --> 00:13:24.000
kind of production implementation. So that, I think, for us at least, is the big difference,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:29.440
the focus on machine learning. I think one differentiator I would also draw is our data

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:34.799
scientists tend to be more comfortable working with lower-level data or data in different formats.

00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:39.919
So not only are they more comfortable working with machine learning, but they're also more

00:13:39.919 --> 00:13:44.719
comfortable working with data in different formats. So not just consuming data from databases,

00:13:44.719 --> 00:13:52.799
but getting into semi-structured, unstructured data, being able to curate those views themselves,

00:13:52.799 --> 00:13:59.679
clean the data, manipulate the data, build features out of it. Most of the analysts we see

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:04.159
tend to be more comfortable consuming data that's already been

00:14:04.239 --> 00:14:10.960
structured into a database, and they're doing more of the high-level analysis on top of it.

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:17.359
So that's another distinction I draw. And then I also think that the focus on putting code into

00:14:17.359 --> 00:14:25.919
production is something that data scientists tend to do more so than analysts. So building a model,

00:14:26.479 --> 00:14:32.960
deriving insights from it, building reports is important, but there's sort of another level

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:37.359
of consideration when you have to think about how a model is going to interact in a production

00:14:37.359 --> 00:14:42.799
process. What data is going to be available? What's the context of a prediction within a

00:14:42.799 --> 00:14:47.679
business process? How is the data going to be fed through that model? Those are some really

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:53.919
important and can be very tricky considerations that if you're not building models, you're not

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:57.919
that if you're not building models for production, you don't really have to think about.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.280
So that's sort of how I think about the distinction within Geico. That said, these

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:10.159
terms are fluid across the industry. What I described in terms of a data scientist at Geico,

00:15:11.039 --> 00:15:18.080
another company might think of as an ML engineer. So I think it's really important if you're

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:23.359
interviewing for a company or considering different jobs to really understand what is the

00:15:23.359 --> 00:15:27.119
role for this person in this company, regardless of what the title is.

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:36.320
And I feel like this question of data analysts or data science seems to come up in a lot of

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:40.880
conversations as well. And I know it might be different for some larger organizations

00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:48.799
versus smaller startups, but would data analysts sit on a much different team than yours? Or

00:15:48.799 --> 00:15:54.640
do you have both data analysts and data scientists? Within Geico, they're in a different

00:15:54.640 --> 00:16:00.640
team, but we would work collaboratively with them. So anytime we take on a use case,

00:16:01.679 --> 00:16:07.840
we would typically identify partners on a business analyst team, a business process team,

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:11.599
data engineering, and if there's an application team involved,

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:18.080
we sort of build these cross-functional teams to address a particular problem.

00:16:18.799 --> 00:16:22.320
I don't think that's the only model. I think a lot of companies combine them on the same team,

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:27.679
and we've considered the pros and cons of that as well. So I think a lot of times there's

00:16:27.679 --> 00:16:33.119
fluidity between the roles. And especially at smaller companies, I think data scientists are

00:16:33.119 --> 00:16:40.320
often asked to wear many hats, just depending on what that company needs at the time. Maybe

00:16:41.359 --> 00:16:46.960
the best way to help them is by creating a dashboard or putting out some basic summary

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:53.200
statistics and analysis on that. I think a lot of data scientists I've run into and interviewing

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:58.640
in just different settings kind of get frustrated by that because they come into the job, the

00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:02.159
industry thinking, you know, I'm going to build machine learning models, or I'm going to do deep

00:17:02.159 --> 00:17:06.800
learning. And I certainly think it's important to find a role that fits in with what you're

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:12.000
looking for. But I would also stress that, especially early in your career, being willing

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:16.640
to kind of roll your sleeves up and get involved in whatever's needed is really critical. And you'll

00:17:17.119 --> 00:17:22.079
develop a lot of good experience in that as well. So even if you find yourself doing a lot of low

00:17:22.079 --> 00:17:26.959
level database work, and it's not really what you're looking for long term, I think there's

00:17:26.959 --> 00:17:31.599
a lot of valuable learning to that. So I would certainly encourage you to take advantage of

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:39.920
those opportunities and be flexible and willing to contribute value however you can for the company

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:46.800
that you're working with. Definitely. Thank you, Joel. And I'm seeing quite a few anonymous

00:17:46.800 --> 00:17:52.000
questions coming in as well from Slido. And kind of going back to what you were initially talking

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:57.920
about, about things that changed during the pandemic and looking more into, or when people

00:17:57.920 --> 00:18:04.719
were driving less, did the pandemic force more data science resources to be put into front facing

00:18:04.719 --> 00:18:12.400
customer experience initiatives? It's hard for me to say broadly. I don't, that was certainly not

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:17.359
the case at GEICO. We're a bigger organization, so we have more specialization and teams that kind

00:18:17.359 --> 00:18:26.239
of focus on those aspects. It definitely impacted us to a degree. You know, initiatives that we were

00:18:26.239 --> 00:18:30.079
working on were maybe steered in a direction that could directly contribute to something more

00:18:30.079 --> 00:18:36.000
pandemic related. So I think there were some small examples of that, but I don't think it was

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:43.040
a wholesale redirection of resources within our company, at least. I would strongly suspect that

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:50.719
that answer would be different at other companies. I think in insurance, we were certainly fortunate

00:18:50.719 --> 00:18:58.479
to not be as directly impacted as some other companies like service industry, for example,

00:18:58.479 --> 00:19:02.640
hotel industries. There were huge impacts for some of those areas, and

00:19:04.959 --> 00:19:07.359
I expect the answer would be different for people working there.

00:19:10.160 --> 00:19:15.520
Thank you. I'll jump back to a few of the anonymous questions in a second here as well,

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:22.079
but I see, Frank, you weighed in in the chat. Would you want to jump in and ask that question

00:19:22.079 --> 00:19:28.640
live too? It's hard for me not to ask questions, so thank you. Joel, you got me really curious

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:34.560
talking about data and models and then figuring out how to give safer drivers better rates.

00:19:35.119 --> 00:19:42.880
It got my mind thinking again about this is sort of a data governance question, and you could say,

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:47.680
you know what, we're only using the data for people that opt in, but sort of automatically

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:53.680
by doing that, you're learning about the people that don't opt in. I'm kind of curious, what is

00:19:53.680 --> 00:19:59.680
your experience? Do you have any comments or thoughts on what I see as sort of a moral hazard

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:08.000
there? Yeah, that's a great question. That's something I think we had talked about for years

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:16.880
as a sort of complicating factor for moving forward with telematics. If it's an opt-in program,

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:22.719
you've got some self-selection bias, and you sort of have to think through whether the economic

00:20:22.719 --> 00:20:31.760
incentives of that align with your business goals. I guess one thing I would say is

00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:38.319
there are different ways of getting telematics information, and some of them have higher

00:20:38.319 --> 00:20:42.959
adoption rates, higher opt-in rates than others. So, you know, for example, one source is connected

00:20:42.959 --> 00:20:49.199
vehicles, and people may or may not know this, but when you're at the dealership

00:20:49.199 --> 00:20:53.599
buying a car, and you're signing through the million sheets of paper or whatever, one of those

00:20:53.599 --> 00:21:00.959
is in all likelihood opting into some sort of monitoring for your driving behavior.

00:21:00.959 --> 00:21:06.239
It might be bundled in with some kind of entertainment package or OnStar or SiriusXM or

00:21:06.239 --> 00:21:13.680
whatever. So, you know, there's some ethical considerations there, of course, but that also

00:21:13.680 --> 00:21:22.160
does kind of shape a little bit of the objectivity or the comprehensiveness of the data that you

00:21:22.160 --> 00:21:30.239
have access to. To the larger question, though, I think this honestly just has to, it's an evolving

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:36.479
picture, right? So, initially, you'll have some limited adoption, and you know your data is biased

00:21:36.479 --> 00:21:42.239
by that, but it's also the population that you're trying to estimate, right? I mean, the way

00:21:42.239 --> 00:21:46.719
you're applying it is the people opting in. So, in some sense, that is the most relevant population

00:21:46.719 --> 00:21:52.800
to analyze, but that will evolve over time as there are other incentives for people to kind of

00:21:52.800 --> 00:21:58.400
join the party and contribute their data. So, I just think you have to keep considering the evolving

00:21:58.400 --> 00:22:06.479
profile of people that opt in. And, you know, I think the larger point in this scenario and others

00:22:06.479 --> 00:22:14.000
is making sure that there is a value to the customer so that it feels like a worthwhile

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:21.920
trade-off for them. You know, people, millions of people, most everyone has a smartphone these days.

00:22:22.479 --> 00:22:26.880
You're giving up a whole lot of data just by owning that smartphone. And, you know, I think

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:32.239
some of the smartphone companies have made a lot of progress in giving people more control

00:22:32.239 --> 00:22:39.119
of what information they're giving up, which is important. But, and you do see various levels of

00:22:39.119 --> 00:22:46.000
concern and backlash in particular scenarios where companies are misusing data. But, overall, I think

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:51.760
a lot of people feel like they're getting value out of services like Facebook or YouTube, TikTok,

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:58.560
whatever. And, you know, as long as they feel like there's an equal exchange for what they're

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:04.640
giving up, I think people are increasingly getting comfortable with that. So, I don't know if that

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:09.199
was a direct answer to your question, but it's not an easy, it's not an easy thing to consider,

00:23:09.199 --> 00:23:13.439
but it's an important thing when you're doing practical data science, practical machine learning

00:23:13.439 --> 00:23:18.560
to kind of think about these second order effects of, you know, not only who is opting into this, but

00:23:19.359 --> 00:23:27.119
what impact does my model have, for example, right? You come in with some historical data about

00:23:27.119 --> 00:23:31.760
who buys what products and whatever, you build a recommender system, but that system itself is

00:23:31.760 --> 00:23:37.839
going to be biasing who purchases what products. And, you know, how do you plan for that bias when

00:23:37.839 --> 00:23:46.079
you're trying to, you know, retrain models or continue to develop them and prevent, you know,

00:23:46.079 --> 00:23:50.800
building echo chambers, for example. So, I think it requires a lot of thought, a lot of

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:54.959
it's use case specific, but it's a really important consideration for people doing practical

00:23:55.520 --> 00:24:02.079
data science work. Yeah, I think you mentioned second and third order effects, that's probably

00:24:02.079 --> 00:24:09.119
the more interesting point because I think all of the single applications that we create and

00:24:09.119 --> 00:24:12.719
all the models that we're building, we could probably justify each of them individually,

00:24:12.719 --> 00:24:16.640
right? There's probably always a good reason. And to be honest, the person that's driving 60

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:20.719
miles an hour down my residential street, I hope they're paying way more in car. You should actually

00:24:20.719 --> 00:24:26.959
charge that person more money, but yeah, it's probably a matter of like the micros are okay,

00:24:26.959 --> 00:24:32.000
but then you put those all together and you're like, oh man, that's a, now we have a moral

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:37.599
conundrum that we need to deal with more as an industry or society. So, I appreciate that.

00:24:37.599 --> 00:24:42.000
Absolutely. I think as a data scientist, you always have to be considering the broader picture. How is

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:47.359
my model going to be used? Is that a valid use of the model given what I know about the data that

00:24:47.359 --> 00:24:53.920
went into it and how it was trained? I think there are a lot of pitfalls that several people have

00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:59.760
pointed out in recent years for misapplying models. So, it's definitely something that

00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:05.199
data scientists need to be aware of. Kind of to your point though about incentives and making

00:25:05.199 --> 00:25:10.079
sure people are being charged the right amount for how they're driving. I think one of the

00:25:10.959 --> 00:25:16.800
real true selling points about telematics for insurance pricing is that the user is in control.

00:25:18.319 --> 00:25:22.959
