If you are in that position or maybe comparing like a huge company like Geico and building

00:30:44.319 --> 00:30:49.040
out that data science team to a startup, what do you think that a startup should

00:30:49.599 --> 00:30:52.719
focus on initially with building out data science?

00:30:52.959 --> 00:31:03.199
Well, data science really relies on a solid foundation of data engineering. So I would say,

00:31:03.839 --> 00:31:09.119
you know, if you think data science or machine learning is eventually going to be a big

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:16.400
contributor to your bottom line, getting really good at collecting and organizing data

00:31:17.199 --> 00:31:22.719
is a great place to start because I think some companies who haven't really

00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:28.880
dealt with that fundamental infrastructure hear a lot about all the cool things that

00:31:28.880 --> 00:31:34.880
data scientists are doing and big technology companies or internet companies, and they think,

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:39.040
oh, I'm just going to hire a bunch of data scientists and I'm going to be able to do

00:31:39.040 --> 00:31:45.359
all these really exciting things. And what that often leads to is a frustrated data science team

00:31:45.359 --> 00:31:52.239
because they find out that the data they need is scattered across dozens of different databases

00:31:52.239 --> 00:31:56.800
and different environments, different formats, and that's where they end up spending all of

00:31:56.800 --> 00:32:04.800
their time pre-processing and building databases just before they can even get to delivering

00:32:04.800 --> 00:32:10.640
insights or building models. So I think thinking through your data architecture and your data

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:13.920
strategy early on is pretty critical in my view.

00:32:17.119 --> 00:32:22.239
Could you maybe define like levels of data science maturity for companies?

