00:35:58.159 --> 00:36:02.560
Yeah, it's a great question. So I'll answer kind of the general question of, you know,

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:06.080
how do you know your models are working? And then, you know, I think there was certainly an

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:09.040
ethical AI component to your question, too, which we can talk about.

00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:15.600
In general, when you're evaluating a machine learning system, I think of three levels of

00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:22.959
monitoring. One is the sort of infrastructure monitoring, the technical system monitoring, you

00:36:22.959 --> 00:36:28.959
know, this is a piece of software, it's a, you know, maybe a web service or whatever, and you

00:36:28.959 --> 00:36:35.840
need to understand how that system is performing and making sure that, you know, it's able to

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:41.679
handle the volume of requests that are coming into it, you're not seeing, you know, large error

00:36:41.679 --> 00:36:45.679
rates, things like that. So there's a sort of low-level technical monitoring that's important.

00:36:45.679 --> 00:36:52.879
Then there is what I would call statistical monitoring, which is, is the model reliably

00:36:52.879 --> 00:36:58.959
predicting what it was trained to predict? You know, are the distribution of the feature inputs

00:36:58.959 --> 00:37:05.120
changing over time? Is the distribution of score changing over time? You know, that's, I think,

00:37:05.120 --> 00:37:09.199
a very important diagnostic to understand, you know, whether it's time to retrain your model

00:37:09.199 --> 00:37:17.600
because you see drift or, you know, whether there's some change in the population that's

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:21.600
being scored through your model. Those are really important. And then there's the third, which I

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:27.199
think gets closer to what you're asking about, which is what are the downstream business impacts

00:37:27.199 --> 00:37:32.080
of the prediction? So, you know, you're predicting whatever it is that you're trying to predict,

00:37:32.080 --> 00:37:36.879
but then there's often actions that are taken based on that prediction. And typically there

00:37:36.879 --> 00:37:44.800
are business KPIs or maybe other considerations that are associated with those actions. And so

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:49.919
we would typically set up monitoring for some of those things as well. And I think it's important

00:37:49.919 --> 00:37:57.040
to have all three levels. To your point about, you know, how models impact people's lives and,

00:37:57.040 --> 00:38:01.040
you know, how they might disparately impact certain groups over others. I mean, it's

00:38:02.399 --> 00:38:09.520
very important and I think a field that's, or a topic that's getting a lot of

00:38:11.120 --> 00:38:17.520
consideration over the recent months and years. Personally, I don't think there's an easy answer

00:38:17.520 --> 00:38:24.159
to it. I think it requires an investigation of specific use cases, you know, how the model

00:38:24.159 --> 00:38:28.560
interacts with different groups of people. What is the intended impact versus what the actual

00:38:28.560 --> 00:38:35.600
impact is? You know, so for example, so there's a lot of talk about AI bias and, you know,

00:38:35.600 --> 00:38:43.360
how predictions skew toward one group or another. And, you know, one answer might be saying, well,

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:49.280
we don't want there to be any skew across certain demographic groups. But I think,

00:38:50.159 --> 00:38:53.439
and I understand what's behind that, and I think in some cases that might be the answer.

00:38:54.159 --> 00:38:58.320
But I also think in some cases that's not really the intent. You know, if you think about, for

00:38:58.320 --> 00:39:05.840
example, a product recommendation engine and something like gender. I think a lot of people

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:11.520
would expect and would want there to be some bias in product recommendations across gender.

00:39:12.479 --> 00:39:16.560
But in some cases, they might have problems with certain recommendations being targeted at

00:39:16.639 --> 00:39:23.280
one gender or another. So there's some nuance there, and it's hard to set a global policy

00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:29.120
that I think covers all cases. So again, I think it's one of those things that a data scientist

00:39:29.120 --> 00:39:33.280
needs to be aware of. They need to know how their model is going to be used, and they need to

00:39:35.120 --> 00:39:38.800
ensure that that is consistent with the data that's being fed into it

00:39:39.439 --> 00:39:42.719
and the methodology that's used to make those predictions.

