jump in and ask that one? Sure, I'll try to do it quickly. So it's related to your three

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:26.320
buckets of monitoring or when Trevor asked how do you know if your models are working or right

00:51:27.199 --> 00:51:34.080
and you had mentioned that in that last, that third bucket, we set up monitoring for those

00:51:34.080 --> 00:51:39.840
things as well and I found it very challenging. You can make predictions statistically, right,

00:51:39.840 --> 00:51:43.679
your bucket number two, hey things are all good, these are good predictions, you should use them

00:51:43.679 --> 00:51:50.320
to make decisions. Trying to capture when those predictions are used as an input to the decision,

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:57.120
I find that sometimes naturally it can happen where there's a system where there's a

00:51:57.120 --> 00:52:03.120
record, but most of the time it is very hard to tell if the predictions are being used.

00:52:04.239 --> 00:52:09.679
I come from retail, I'm in the supply chain world, a lot of what we do is still manual,

00:52:09.679 --> 00:52:14.959
maybe it's different in your world and if so I'd like to hear about that. Yeah, no it's an

00:52:14.959 --> 00:52:20.560
important point. I think the stronger the connection between the model prediction and

00:52:20.560 --> 00:52:24.479
the action, the easier it is to measure, but that's not always the case. I mean sometimes

00:52:25.439 --> 00:52:33.120
you're providing guidance or recommendations and it's still ultimately up to the decision maker to

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:39.040
factor that in along with many other things and so attributing a specific action to the

00:52:39.040 --> 00:52:44.800
model can be difficult. I don't know that there's an easy answer to that all the time,

00:52:44.800 --> 00:52:50.320
some of that can be handled though through good experimental design. So you know maybe,

00:52:50.320 --> 00:52:54.560
you know in your case in retail, maybe there there's a way of only rolling out a product

00:52:54.560 --> 00:52:57.919
in a subset of stores and then you compare that to the stores where it's not. So even

00:52:58.800 --> 00:53:03.360
if you can't grow stores, had access to that prediction and this other group didn't

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:08.719
and you hope that through your experimental design you've randomized enough for some of

00:53:08.719 --> 00:53:16.000
the other confounding factors and you're able to draw valid inferences about the impact of that.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:19.199
So I think you just have to think through the experimental design, how you're going to measure

00:53:19.199 --> 00:53:26.000
that, keeping in mind just what the business case is and how the prediction is being used.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:31.040
Yeah for sure, does your team, are there, do they do anything, are they responsible for that,

00:53:31.040 --> 00:53:34.320
is there another team that uses your models and then does the experimental design?

