what we're doing at Geico or provide any you know advice based on my experience and you know working

00:58:15.360 --> 00:58:22.479
in data science. Feel free to reach out. Great, thank you Joel. And one other question I wanted

00:58:22.479 --> 00:58:27.840
to ask is, I know there's a bunch of people on the call who may be aspiring data science leaders

00:58:27.840 --> 00:58:34.159
and what feedback would you or advice would you give to someone hoping to move into a leadership

00:58:34.159 --> 00:58:41.600
role? Really pay attention to the business, right? Because ultimately you're there to drive business

00:58:42.320 --> 00:58:47.840
results and you know the technology, the methodologies, the statistics and data science

00:58:47.840 --> 00:58:53.679
are really interesting. You can dive as deep as you want in that area and have a great career

00:58:54.479 --> 00:58:58.399
and be fulfilled in that area. But if you want to move into leadership, you need to learn to

00:58:59.360 --> 00:59:05.360
speak the business language, understand the needs of the business that you're trying to serve,

00:59:06.080 --> 00:59:09.280
and you know through that I think you can be an effective leader and

00:59:09.919 --> 00:59:15.760
understand how to bridge the gap between the technology and the business process that can

00:59:15.760 --> 00:59:21.760
leverage that technology. Because a lot of times, I mean that's honestly a very valuable skill,

00:59:21.760 --> 00:59:25.919
because a lot of people are good at the technical side. They can you know tell you how machine

00:59:25.919 --> 00:59:30.080
learning algorithms work and how to optimize you know the different parameters to predict the value

00:59:30.080 --> 00:59:35.199
but they can't really relate to the business problem. And then on the other side, there's a

00:59:36.159 --> 00:59:41.600
lot of business leaders who have a very high level understanding of machine learning or AI. They've

00:59:41.600 --> 00:59:44.879
read you know Harvard Business Review or something like that, but they don't really

00:59:45.439 --> 00:59:50.959
understand it in meaningful terms. So being someone who can bridge that gap I think is a

00:59:50.959 --> 00:59:58.959
great way to advance into leadership within data science. Wonderful and I completely agree with

